{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. --> | name = Graeme Gibson | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | pseudonym = | birth_name = Graeme C. Gibson | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1934|8|9|df=y}} | birth_place = [[London, Ontario|London]], [[Ontario]], Canada | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|Year|Month|Day|Year|Month|Day}} --> | death_place = | resting_place = | occupation = Novelist | language = | nationality = Canadian | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = | period = | genre = [[Novel]], [[non-fiction]] | subject = | movement = | notableworks = ''Eleven Canadian Novelists'' | spouse =Shirley Gibson (div. c. 1973) | partner = [[Margaret Atwood]] | children = 3 | relatives = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | website = | portaldisp = | ethnicity = | influences = | influenced = }} '''Graeme C. Gibson''', {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|CM}} (born 9 August 1934) is a Canadian [[novelist]].<ref name=canenc>[http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/gibson-graeme/ Graeme Gibson's] entry in [[The Canadian Encyclopedia]].</ref> He is a Member of the [[Order of Canada]] (1992) and was one of the organizers of the [[Writer's Union of Canada]] (chair, 1974–75). He is also a founder of the [[Writers' Trust of Canada]], a non-profit literary organization that seeks to encourage Canada's writing community.<ref name=canenc/> He had two sons, Matt and Grae, with publisher Shirley Gibson.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/apr/26/fiction.margaretatwood|title=Light in the wilderness|last=Potts|first=Robert|date=2003-04-26|work=The Guardian|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.quillandquire.com/authors/the-elusive-margaret-atwood/|title=The elusive Margaret Atwood {{!}} Quill and Quire|date=2004-04-28|work=Quill and Quire|access-date=2017-07-05}}</ref>
Gibson has a long-term relationship with novelist and poet [[Margaret Atwood]] which began in 1973.<ref name=canenc/> They moved to a farm near [[Alliston, Ontario]], where their daughter Eleanor Jess Atwood Gibson was born in 1976. The family returned to [[Toronto]] in 1980.<ref name="Sutherland2012">{{cite book|last=Sutherland|first=John|title=Lives of the Novelists: A History of Fiction in 294 Lives|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aV9ot7kGdi4C&pg=PA721|year=2012|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0-300-18243-9|page=721}}</ref>
He is best known for his 1973 book ''Eleven Canadian Novelists'', a non-fiction work in which he conducted extended interviews about literature and writing with Atwood, [[Austin Clarke (novelist)|Austin Clarke]], [[Matt Cohen (writer)|Matt Cohen]], [[Marian Engel]], [[Timothy Findley]], [[Dave Godfrey]], [[Margaret Laurence]], [[Jack Ludwig]], [[Alice Munro]], [[Mordecai Richler]] and [[Scott Symons]].
In 1996 he decided to stop writing novels. At the time he was working on a novel titled ''Moral Disorder''. Atwood borrowed the title for her [[Moral Disorder|collection of short stories]] published in 2006.<ref>See the Acknowledgements at the end of Margaret Atwood, ''Moral Disorder'', McClelland and Stewart, 2006.</ref> He is a former council member of [[World Wildlife Fund]] Canada and is chairman of [[Pelee Island]] Bird Observatory.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}}
He was awarded, jointly with [[Jacob Verhoef]] and Margaret Atwood, the 2015 Gold Medal of the [[Royal Canadian Geographical Society]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rcgs.org/awards/gold_medal/winner_gold2015.asp|title= Gold Medal 2015 Recipients - Dr. Jacob Verhoef, Graeme Gibson and Margaret Atwood|publisher= Royal Canadian Geographical Society|accessdate = 21 November 2015}}</ref>
''[[The New Yorker]]'' magazine reported in its April 17, 2017 edition that Gibson has been diagnosed with early signs of dementia.
