==Additional examples==
[[File:Asteroid2006DP14.jpg|thumb|Radar-imaging of [[2006 DP14]], which passed by Earth in early February 2014 at a distance of 6.25 [[Lunar distance (astronomy)|LD]]]]
An example list of near-Earth asteroids that passed more than 1 lunar distance (384,400&nbsp;km or 0.00256 AU) from Earth in 2014.
*{{mpl|(388188) 2006 DP|14}} (~300 meters in diameter) passed 6.2 lunar distances from Earth on 10 February 2014.
*{{mpl|2000 EM|26}} (~200 meters in diameter) passed more than {{convert|0.018|AU|km mi|abbr=on|lk=on}} from Earth on 17–18 February 2014.
*{{mp|2014 HJ|197}} (~3 meters in diameter) may have passed as close as 0.97 lunar distances (371,000&nbsp;km) from Earth (0.68 lunar distances (261,000&nbsp;km) from the Moon on either April 14 or 15th, 2014, but the nominal orbit calculates an approach of 1.29 lunar distances (495,000&nbsp;km) from Earth (1.23 lunar distances (473,000&nbsp;km) from the Moon).
*{{mp|2014 KH|39}} (~25 meters in diameter) passed 1.1 lunar distances from Earth on 3 June 2014.<ref>[http://www.universetoday.com/112296/asteroid-2014-kh39-zips-just-1-1-ld-from-earth-watch-it-live-june-3/ B. King - Asteroid 2014 KH39 Zips Just 1.1 LD from Earth - Universe Today]</ref>
*{{mpl|2014 HQ|124}} (~325 meters in diameter) passed 3.25 lunar distances from Earth on 8 June 2014.
*{{mpl|2014 OO|6}} (~75 meters in diameter) passed {{convert|0.0297|AU|km mi|abbr=on|lk=off}} from Earth on 18 August 2014.
*{{mpl|2014 XL|7}} (~230 meters in diameter) passed roughly {{convert|0.26|AU|km mi|abbr=on|lk=off}} from Earth on 1 September 2014.
*The orbit of [[2009 RR]] (20–45 meters in diameter) with an observation arc of only 4 days predicted that it could pass just inside 1 lunar distance on 2014-09-16, but the orbital uncertainties show that it could have passed as much as {{convert|0.1|AU|km mi|abbr=on|lk=off}} from Earth.<ref name="2009RR">{{cite web |url=http://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=2009RR;cad=1#cad |title=JPL Small-Body Database Browser: (2009 RR) |type=last observation: 2009-09-15; arc: 4 days}}</ref>
*{{mp|2014 SN|142}} (~10 meters in diameter) passed 1.1 lunar distances from Earth on 23 September 2014.<ref name="2014SN142">{{cite web |url=http://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=2014SN142;cad=1#cad |title=JPL Small-Body Database Browser: (2014 SN142) |type=last observation: 2014-09-22}}</ref>
*{{mpl|2014 SC|324}} (~60 meters in diameter) passed 1.5 lunar distances from Earth on 24 October 2014.<ref name="2014SC324">{{cite web |url=http://ssd.jpl.nasa.gov/sbdb.cgi?sstr=2014SC324;cad=1#cad |title=JPL Small-Body Database Browser: (2014 SC324) |type=last observation: 2014-10-24}}</ref>

