{{update|date=April 2018}} {{Infobox power station | name = María Elena Solar Power Plant | name_official = | image = Comuna de María Elena.svg | image_size = | image_caption = Thermosolar plant | image_alt = | location_map = Chile | coordinates = {{coord|22|10|S|69|25|W|type:landmark_region:CL-AN|display=inline,title}} | country = [[Chile]] | location = [[Antofagasta Region|Antofagasta]] | status = Project approved | construction_began = | commissioned = | decommissioned = | cost = | owner = | operator = | solar_type = CSP | solar_csp_technology = T | ps_units_operational = 4 | solar_csp_heliostats = | ps_units_manu_model = | ps_electrical_capacity = 400&nbsp;MW | ps_electrical_cap_fac = | ps_annual_generation = 110 [[GWh]] | website = | extra = }}
'''María Elena Solar Power Plant''' (Spanish: '''''Planta Termosolar María Elena''''') is a [[concentrated solar power]] plant with a [[Thermal energy storage#Molten-salt technology|molten-salt technology]] system that is currently under construction{{cn|date=April 2018}} in the [[Communes of Chile|commune]] of [[María Elena]] in the [[Antofagasta Region]] of Chile.<ref>[http://www.thisischile.cl/8861/2/Chile-greenlights-enormous-400-megawatt-solar-project/News.aspx Here comes the sun Chile greenlights enormous 400-megawatt solar project] www.thisischile.cl Friday, August 23, 2013 retrieved August 30, 2013</ref>
The María Elena complex will be made up of four separate 100&nbsp;MW plants,<ref>[http://www.bnamericas.com/project-profile/en/planta-termosolar-maria-elena-termosolar-maria-elena Planta Termosolar María Elena] www.bnamericas.com retrieved August 30, 2013</ref> for a total capacity of 400 MW, and will supply the northern SING (Sistema Interconectado del Norte Gande) grid via a 17.5&nbsp;km, 220&nbsp;kV double circuit transmission line connected to the Encuentro substation. The $3.6 billion thermo solar plant will be the largest plant of its kind in the world. The project is being developed by [[Ibereólica Solar Atacama]], a subsidiary of [[Madrid]]-based [[Grupo Ibereólica]]. It will employ 1,500 workers during the construction stage and 200 as permanent staff when in operation. Construction will take 27 months so the plant will be operational in July 2016 at the earliest.<ref>[http://www.estrategia.cl/detalle_noticia.php?cod=69658 Ingresa a evaluación ambiental mayor planta termosolar del mundo] www.estrategia.cl December 12, 2012 retrieved September 2, 2013</ref>
