[[Category:Bayer objects|Sagittarii, Theta]] [[Category:Sagittarius (constellation)]]

{{Multiple issues|{{refimprove|date=October 2014}}{{orphan|date=October 2014}}}}

'''Tree box filters'''<ref>http://www.ianrpubs.unl.edu/epublic/live/ec701/build/ec701.pdf| "Stormwater Terminology" 2011. University of Nebraska Press Extension Curricular</ref> are typically filtration systems installed under a street or sidewalk which have trees planted in them.  The systems collect [[stormwater]] runoff through methods such as permeable pavers or curb cuts.  The runoff is then filtered by soil, microbes and vegetation before either being utilized by the tree or discharged into a [[storm drain]] system.

==Benefits==

Tree box filters have the potential to improve the quality and health of street trees by providing larger areas for roots to stabilize the tree and more availability of water and nutrients. Additionally, the filters can delay the [[peak flow]] and improve the [[water quality]] of [[water]] entering a storm drain system. It is a practical management strategy for stormwater issues in urban settings.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Geronimo|first=Franz Kevin F.|last2=Maniquiz-Redillas|first2=Marla C.|last3=Kim|first3=Lee-Hyung|date=2013-05-01|title=Treatment of parking lot runoff by a tree box filter|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1080/19443994.2013.781099|journal=Desalination and Water Treatment|volume=51|issue=19-21|pages=4044–4049|doi=10.1080/19443994.2013.781099|issn=1944-3994}}</ref> 

